Sub-Sahara Africa Stocks: Access Bank; Ghana Commercial Bank

-- B y   C h r i s   K a y
-- 
2011-09-02T15:32:27Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-09-02/sub-sahara-africa-stocks-access-bank-ghana-commercial-bank.html
Kenya’s All-Share Index declined for
a second day, falling 0.5 percent to 60.44 by the 3 p.m. end of
trading in Nairobi, the lowest level since January 2010.  The Ghana Stock Exchange Composite Index retreated for a
second day, tumbling 1.1 percent to 1,125.21 by the 3 p.m. close
in Accra, the weakest close since May 3.  Namibia ’s FTSE/ Namibia Overall Index (FTN098)  snapped two days of
gains, slumping 3 percent to 780.52 by the 4 p.m. close in
Windhoek, the biggest fall since Aug. 18. The Nigerian Stock
Exchange All-Share Index jumped 1.4 percent to 21,598.98 by the
2:30 p.m. close in Lagos, according to a statement on the
bourse’s website. The Stock Exchange of Mauritius was closed
today for a public holiday.  The following shares rose or fell in sub-Saharan  Africa ,
excluding  South Africa . Stock symbols are in parentheses.  Access Bank Plc (ACCESS)  , a Nigerian lender, jumped 28
kobo, or 5 percent, to 5.91 naira, the biggest gain since Jan.
6, after saying its plans to buy Intercontinental Bank Plc will
be completed next year.  Ghana Commercial Bank (GCB GN), the West African nation’s
biggest lender, retreated 14 pesewas, or 4.9 percent, to 2.7
cedis, the biggest decline since Dec. 15. Emerging-market stocks
fell for the first time in six days after hiring in the U.S.
unexpectedly stagnated as U.S. employers became less confident
in the recovery of the world’s largest economy, before the close
of the Ghana Stock Exchange.  To contact the reporter on this story:
